==English==

===Etymology===
Back-formation from ''part-taking'', a Middle English calque of Latin {{term|particeps||participating|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GenAm}} {{enPR|pär-tāk'}}, {{IPA|/pɑɹˈteɪk/}}
* {{a|RP}} {{enPR|pär-tāk'}}, {{IPA|/pɑːˈteɪk/}}
* {{audio|en-us-partake.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|eɪk}}
* {{hyphenation|par|take}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|partakes|partaking|partook|partaken}}

# {{context|intransitive|formal|lang=en}} To take part in an activity; to [[participate]].
#* John Locke
#*: Brutes '''partake''' in this faculty.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To take a [[share]] or [[portion]] (of).
#: ''Will you '''partake''' of some food?''
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To have something of the properties, character, or office (of).
#* Francis Bacon
#*: The attorney of the Duchy of Lancaster '''partakes''' partly of a judge, and partly of an attorney-general.

